<worksheet label="ws-PA-exp-log-properties">
  <exploration xml:id="PA-exp-log-properties">
    <introduction>
      <p>
			In the following questions, we investigate how <m>\log_{10}(a \cdot b)</m> can be equivalently written in terms of <m>\log_{10}(a)</m> and  <m>\log_{10}(b)</m>.
		</p>
      <p/>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="3cm" xml:id="PA-exp-log-properties-task-0">
      <statement>
        <p>
						Write <m>10^x \cdot 10^y</m> as <m>10</m> raised to a single power.  That is, complete the equation
						<me>
							10^x \cdot 10^y = 10^{\Box}
						</me>
						by filling in the box with an appropriate expression involving <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.
					</p>
      </statement>
      <hint/>
      <answer/>
      <solution/>
    </task>
    <task workspace="3cm" xml:id="PA-exp-log-properties-task-1">
      <statement>
        <p>
						What is the simplest possible way to write <m>\log_{10}10^x</m>?  What about the simplest equivalent expression for <m>\log_{10}10^y</m>?
					</p>
      </statement>
      <hint/>
      <answer/>
      <solution/>
    </task>
    <task workspace="3cm" xml:id="PA-exp-log-properties-task-2">
      <statement>
        <p>
						Explain why each of the following three equal signs is valid in the sequence of equalities:
						<md><mrow>\log_{10}(10^x \cdot 10^y) &amp;= \log_{10}(10^{x+y})</mrow><mrow>         &amp;= x+y</mrow><mrow>         &amp;= \log_{10}(10^x) + \log_{10}(10^y)</mrow></md>.
					</p>
      </statement>
      <hint/>
      <answer/>
      <solution/>
    </task>
    <task workspace="3cm" xml:id="PA-exp-log-properties-task-3">
      <statement>
        <m>a</m>
        <m>b</m>
        <m>a</m>
        <m>10^x</m>
        <m>x</m>
        <m>b</m>
        <m>10^y</m>
        <m>y</m>
        <m>a = 10^x</m>
        <m>b = 10^y</m>
        <m>\log_{10}(ab)</m>
      </statement>
      <hint/>
      <answer/>
      <solution/>
    </task>
  </exploration>
</worksheet>
